Survival Analysis for subtypes of HGG/DMG

C. Savonen for ALSF CCDL, Krutika Gaonkar for D3B

2019

Purpose:

Runs survival analysis models for subtypes of Diffuse astrocytic and oligodendroglial tumors

Usage

Uses a wrapper function (survival_analysis) from utils folder.

Setup

Packages and functions

Read in set up script.

# This script contains a wrapper function that can conduct the survival analyses
source(file.path("util", "survival_models.R"))

# Magrittr pipe
`%>%` <- dplyr::`%>%`

Set up files and directories

Set up output directories.

data_dir <- file.path("..", "..", "data")
results_dir <- "results"
plots_dir <- "plots"

Make output directories.

if (!dir.exists(results_dir)) {
  dir.create(results_dir)
}
if (!dir.exists(plots_dir)) {
  dir.create(plots_dir)
}

Declare input file paths.

metadata_file <- file.path(data_dir, "pbta-histologies.tsv")
independent_primary_file <- file.path(data_dir, "independent-specimens.wgswxs.primary.tsv")

Declare output file paths for HGG/DMG all subtypes.

kap_meier_plot_file <- file.path(plots_dir, "survival_curve_HGG_DMG.pdf")
kap_meier_model_file <- file.path(results_dir,"survival_model_HGG_DMG.tsv")

Import the metadata

# choose Diffuse astrocytic and oligodendroglial tumor samples
# remove RNA-Seq because subtyping in HGG is from DNA abberations and samples where only RNA-Seq is available cannot be subtyped
# remove cell-lines from this analysis as well
metadata <- readr::read_tsv(metadata_file,
                            col_types = readr::cols(molecular_subtype = readr::col_character())) %>%
  filter(experimental_strategy!="RNA-Seq" & 
           broad_histology=="Diffuse astrocytic and oligodendroglial tumor" &
           broad_composition !="cell-line") %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# find patients where multiple subtypes are present 
count_patient_subtype<-metadata %>% 
  select(Kids_First_Participant_ID ,molecular_subtype) %>%
  unique() %>%
  group_by(Kids_First_Participant_ID ) %>% 
  summarise(count=n(),subtype=toString(molecular_subtype)) %>%
  filter(count>1)

# these patients might affect downstream analysis for survival and would need to be removed
count_patient_subtype
NA

Let’s use independent_primary to use primary samples only and maybe will help filter cases where multiple subtypes are present per patient ID

Ok so no patients with multiple subtypes now.

Kaplan-Meier for all HGG/DMG subtypes

The Kaplan-Meier survival curve shows the probability of survival over time.

kap_fit <- survival_analysis(metadata,
  ind_var = "molecular_subtype",
  test = "kap.meier",
  metadata_sample_col = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID"
)

survminer package comes with a convenient plotting function which uses ggplot2 arguments. It requires the original Kaplain-Meier survfit object, so we will extract that with $model.

surv_plot <- survminer::ggsurvplot(kap_fit$model,
  pval = TRUE,
  data = kap_fit$original_data,
  risk.table = TRUE,
  xlim = c(0, 3000),
  break.time.by = 500,
  ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
  risk.table.y.text.col = TRUE,
  risk.table.y.text = FALSE
) 
Vectorized input to `element_text()` is not officially supported.
Results may be unexpected or may change in future versions of ggplot2.
surv_plot$plot<-surv_plot$plot+ggtitle(paste0("Kap_meier_Diffuse_astrocytic_and_oligodendroglial_tumor"))+theme(legend.position = "right")

# Make this plot a combined plot
surv_plot_all_subtype <- cowplot::plot_grid(surv_plot[[1]], surv_plot[[2]], nrow = 2, 
                                rel_heights = c(3, 2))

# Print it out here

Save the plot to a file.

# We can save the plot like a normal ggplot
cowplot::save_plot(filename = kap_meier_plot_file, plot = surv_plot_all_subtype)
# Let's save the model for CI and median survial as well
write_tsv(surv_median(kap_fit$model),kap_meier_model_file)

Subtypes comapred to wildtype

Lets look at Kap Meier plots for each mutant subtype to H3 wildtype


list_subtypes<-c("DMG, H3 K28","BRAF V600E","HGG, H3 G35","HGG, IDH","DMG, H3 K28, BRAF V600E")
for (i in 1:length(list_subtypes)){
  kap_meier_plot_file <- file.path(plots_dir,paste0("Kap_meier_Diffuse_astrocytic_and_oligodendroglial_tumor_",gsub(" ","_",list_subtypes[i]),".pdf"))
  kap_meier_model_file <- file.path(results_dir,paste0("Kap_meier_Diffuse_astrocytic_and_oligodendroglial_tumor_",gsub(" ","_",list_subtypes[i]),".tsv"))
  metadata_test<-metadata %>% 
    filter(molecular_subtype %in% c(list_subtypes[i],"HGG, H3 wildtype") )
  kap_fit <- survival_analysis(metadata_test,
                               ind_var = "molecular_subtype",
                               test = "kap.meier",
                               metadata_sample_col = "Kids_First_Biospecimen_ID"
  )
  
  #plot curve
  surv_plot <- survminer::ggsurvplot(kap_fit$model,
                                     pval = TRUE,
                                     data = kap_fit$original_data,
                                     risk.table = TRUE,
                                     xlim = c(0, 3000),
                                     break.time.by = 500,
                                     ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
                                     risk.table.y.text.col = TRUE,
                                     risk.table.y.text = FALSE
  ) 
  
  surv_plot$plot<-surv_plot$plot+ggtitle(paste0("Kap_meier_Diffuse_astrocytic_and_oligodendroglial_tumor"))+theme(legend.position = "right")
  
  # Make this plot a combined plot
  surv_plot <- cowplot::plot_grid(surv_plot[[1]], surv_plot[[2]], nrow = 2, rel_heights = c(2.5, 1))
  
  # Print to file
  cowplot::save_plot(filename = kap_meier_plot_file, plot = surv_plot,base_height = 10)
  # Save to file
  write_tsv(surv_median(kap_fit$model),kap_meier_model_file)
}
